 'ACQUISITION METHODOLOGY: Cascade Investment uses a network of subsidiary companies to acquire farmland without Gates\' name appearing on deeds. Purchases are made through entities like Cottonwood Ag Management, Leading Harvest, and various state-specific LLCs. This opacity obscures the true concentration of ownership.',
 'FOREIGN ACQUISITION CONCERNS: Foreign entities own over 40 million acres of U.S. agricultural land. Chinese-owned companies have acquired land near sensitive military installations. There is minimal federal oversight of foreign farmland purchases despite national security implications.',
 'INSTITUTIONAL INVESTOR INVASION: Private equity firms, REITs, and pension funds are increasingly viewing farmland as an investment asset. Farmland Partners, Gladstone Land, and similar entities own hundreds of thousands of acres. This financialization treats food-producing land as just another asset class.',
 'FAMILY FARMER DISPLACEMENT: The average age of American farmers is 58. When farmers retire or die, their families often sell to the highest bidder - increasingly institutional investors or billionaires. Young farmers cannot compete with institutional capital for land access.',
 'TENANT FARMING RISE: As land concentrates in fewer hands, more farmers become tenants rather than owners. Tenant farmers have less security, less incentive for long-term soil health, and less community investment. America is developing a new class of agricultural serfs.',
 'FOOD SYSTEM CONTROL: Whoever controls the land controls the food supply. Concentrated ownership enables coordination of agricultural practices, crop choices, and pricing. Combined with seed patents and processing monopolies, this creates vertically integrated food system control.',
 'GATES AGRICULTURAL AGENDA: Gates has promoted specific agricultural approaches: GMO crops, synthetic fertilizers, digital agriculture technology. His farmland serves as a testing ground for technologies his other investments produce. Critics question whether this serves farmers or Gates\' portfolio.',
 'POLICY CAPTURE: Agricultural policy increasingly serves large landowners and agribusiness. Farm subsidies flow disproportionately to the largest operations. USDA programs nominally helping small farmers often benefit corporate agriculture. Political donations from ag interests shape policy.',
 'LOCAL IMPACT: Communities built around family farms face economic devastation as land consolidates. Local businesses lose customers. Schools lose students. Rural America becomes economically hollowed out as wealth extracts to distant billionaire owners.',
